    <segment id="1" parent="13" relname="span">Allen (2002) defines intuitiveness as something that is natural. </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
The comprehension of the task would require the users do not have to think about the task when doing it. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
He further concludes that intuitive interfaces donÂ’t go beyond what the user already knows or could figure out from prior experiences.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="12" relname="span">
How intuitiveness is applied in usability is the common understanding in the group, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="elaboration">
the group made up of users familiar with the job and the environment in which the job is preformed.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span"> 

Some of the ways to measure intuitiveness, using the above definition, might be to measure how long it takes users to perform tasks. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="14" relname="span">
These tasks, however, must meet the definition of something they are familiar with, </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration">
or should know from prior experiences. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="sequence">
The measurement could be based on taking someone who has not seen the interface </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="15" relname="sequence">and compare that time against someone more experienced with it.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="18" relname="condition"> 
If the interface is intuitive</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="19" relname="span"> then the time differences should be small. 

</segment>
